<section xml:id="Zmodm">
  <title><m>\mathbb{Z}/m</m></title>
  <p>
    In this section we introduce a set
    <m>\mathbb{Z}/m</m> that will be important your future algebra classes.
    Just like the integers, the rationals,
    and the reals, it is what is called a <term>ring</term>:
    it is equipped with addition,
    subtraction, and multiplication operations.
    Unlike <m>\mathbb{Z}</m>, <m>\mathbb{Q}</m>, or <m>\mathbb{R}</m>,
    the set <m>\mathbb{Z}/m</m> is <term>finite</term>.
  </p>
  <p>
    As a set,
    <me>
      \mathbb{Z}/m=\{0,1,\dots,m-1\}
    </me>.
  </p>
  <p>
    On this set we shall define addition and multiplication operations:
    for any <m>x,y \in \mathbb{Z}/m</m>,
    <me>
      x + y = z \mbox{ where \(z\in \{0,1,...,m-1\}\) is the unique element such that }  x + y = z\mod m
    </me>,
    and
    <me>
      x \cdot y = z \mbox{ where \(z\in \{0,1,...,m-1\}\) is the unique element such that }  x \cdot y = z\mod m
    </me>,
  </p>
  <p>
    There is an additive inverse:
    <me>
      - x = m-x
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    (Some books write <m>\mathbb{Z}_m</m> for <m>\mathbb{Z}/m</m>,
    but most algebraists reserve this notation for a very different object!!)
  </p>
